    "optional_reagent_smiles": [
      "Cl[Rh]([P](c1ccccc1)(c1ccccc1)c1ccccc1)([P](c1ccccc1)(c1ccccc1)c1ccccc1)[P](c1ccccc1)(c1ccccc1)c1ccccc1"
    ],
    "rationale": "This is a classic textbook example of the Tsuji-Wilkinson decarbonylation, converting a simple aliphatic aldehyde (heptanal) to the corresponding alkane (hexane) using Wilkinson's catalyst. The reaction is stoichiometric with respect to the rhodium complex, which is consumed by forming a stable carbonyl complex. The simple, acyclic, saturated aliphatic chain is ideal for a benchmark seed as it clearly illustrates the core C-C bond cleavage of the formyl group without introducing other reactive functional groups or complex stereochemistry.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "The substrate is a simple aliphatic aldehyde, avoiding aromatic rings which could be confused with various cross-coupling or C-H activation reactions. The product is a simple alkane, avoiding motifs associated with other named reactions. The transformation is a clear deformylation, which is specific to this reaction family and distinct from decarboxylation (loss of CO2) or deoxygenation (e.g., Wolff-Kishner, Clemmensen)."
  }
}
